Quo vadis America? Shopping lists still include the usual food staples but also remind one to pick up the ginkgo biloba to boost memory, kava kava to relieve stress, evening primrose oil, black cohosh, and dong quai to relieve PMS and menopausal symptoms, echinacea to enhance immunity, feverfew to reduce migraines, St. John's wort for depression, ginger for motion sickness or nausea, garlic to reduce choles- terol and blood pressure, and don't forget the vale- rian to relieve insomnia. Four of 10 Americans are actively seeking alternative medicine therapies. The therapies that have increased the most include herbal medicine, massage, megavitamins, self-help groups, folk remedies, energy healing, and homeopathy. Vis- its to alternative medicine practitioners increased from 427 million in 1990 to 629 million in 1997. This is a 47.3% increase in total visits. These visits exceed the total visits of 386 million to all U.S. primary care physicians. Additionally, in 1997 an estimated 15 million adults took prescription medi- cations concurrently with herbal remedies and/or high-dose vitamins (18.4% of all prescription users.) Estimated expenditures for alternative medicine pro- fessional services increased 45.2% between 1990 and 1997 and were conservatively estimated at $21.2 billion in 1997, with at least $12.2 billion paid out- of-pocket. This exceeds the 1997 out-of-pocket ex- penditures for all U.S. hospitalizations of $9.1 bil- lion. jected 1997 out-of-pocket expenditures of $29 billion for all U.S. physician services. Considering the upper limit for total out-of-pocket expenditures in 1997, the figure is $34.4 billion. This includes $19.6 billion for professional services, $3.3 billion for megavitamins, $1.7 billion for commercial diet products, $5.1 bil- lion for herbal medicine, and $4.7 billion for therapy- specific books, classes, and equipment. Two other observations on alternative medicine are noteworthy. In 1997, 42% of all alternative therapies were used for treatment of existing medical conditions, whereas 58% were used for prevention and maintaining health. Lastly, less then 40% of users of alternative therapies disclose this use to their physicians (1). These "all-natural" products are often referred to as nutraceuticals or botanicals. They are sold as nutri- tional or dietary supplements, not drugs. This allows these products to be sold directly to consumers with- out going through the Food and Drug Administra- tion's (FDA) approval process. The FDA can only remove a supplement from the market after it has been shown to be hazardous. Because herbal medi- cines do not pass through the FDA approval process, these manufacturers have not conducted well-designed scientific studies to demonstrate their safety and ef- ficacy. Therefore, they may not claim that the prod- uct is intended to diagnose, treat, cure, or prevent any disease. However, a claim may be made that a prod- uct provides energy or enhances mood without refer- ring to a specific medical condition. With the in- creasing use of herbal medicines by approximately 20% of the population who concurrently use pre- scription drugs, potential adverse interactions may become more commonplace.
